The Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) advise against all but essential travel to Botswana. The Botswana authorities have introduced a number of precautionary measures in response to the coronavirus (COVID-19) pandemic. See Health
Given the rapidly changing situation in Botswana we are temporarily withdrawing a limited number of UK staff and their dependents from our High Commission. The High Commission will continue to carry out essential work including providing 24/7 consular assistance and support to British people in Botswana.
The Government of Botswana announced on 16 March new measures restricting individuals entering Botswana if they have come from various countries affected by coronavirus, including the United Kingdom. Returning residents are exempt from these restrictions, but will be subject to a 14-day mandatory quarantine period. Visas will no longer be issued to nationals from countries affected by coronavirus and current visas will be cancelled with immediate effect, except for those already in Botswana.
Many visitors from the UK travel to and from Botswana via South Africa. South Africa has put in place travel restrictions on individuals from countries affected by coronavirus, including the United Kingdom. Follow our travel advice for South Africa for information on South African entry requirements, and consult your nearest South African High Commission.
SA Express suspended flights between all destinations in Botswana and Johannesburg on 18 March 2020 until further notice. Check with the airline or your tour operator before travelling.
Around 42,000 British nationals visit Botswana every year. Most visits are trouble free.
South African Airways is undergoing a business rescue process resulting in changes to its international and domestic flight schedules and some cancellations. Check with the airline or your tour operator before travelling.
Wildlife and livestock on roads are a hazard, particularly at night. See Road travel.
Carry some form of identification with you at all times. A photocopy of your passport is sufficient.
Attacks on tourists are rare, but you should take sensible precautions to protect yourself from petty and violent crime. See Crime.
Although there’s no recent history of terrorism in Botswana, attacks can’t be ruled out. See Terrorism.
If you’re abroad and you need emergency help from the UK government, contact the nearest British embassy, consulate or high commission.
Take out travel and medical insurance before travelling.
